For each of the following scenarios, call out the potential biases in the proposed experiment. 
Do your best to try to discover not only the bias, but the initial design. 
There is plenty of room for interpretation here, so make sure to state what assumptions you're making.

1. You're testing advertising emails for a bathing suit company and you test one version of the email in February and the other in May.
Answer: winter vs spring, hemisphere assumption, geographic location (how far south or north) in said month

You open a clinic to treat anxiety and find that the people who visit show a higher rate of anxiety than the general population.
Answer: sample problem. people who seek out anxiety treatment are more likely to have anxiety. 

You launch a new ad billboard based campaign and see an increase in website visits in the first week.
Answer: correlation doesn't equal causation, and rarely does. this is narrative seeking and ignore all other factors.

You launch a loyalty program but see no change in visits in the first week.
Answer: Loyal customers are loyal as a result of proven buying over time. Better measurement would be over x-months and how that
is different from similar buying patterns.
